Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the C++ iterator that libpcapng
exposes.  It consists of

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface that you will ship to users.
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑stub file that talks to the C++ library and to the
  OCaml runtime.

The two files are enough to build a library that can be linked with an OCaml
program.  A tiny `Makefile` fragment is added at the end to show how to compile
the stubs (you will have to adapt the include / library paths to your own
environment).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml interface
```ocaml
(** {1 libpcapng OCaml binding} *)

(** Abstract handle to a opened pcapng file. *)
type t

(** One captured frame.  The fields are deliberately kept simple – they are
    sufficient for most analysis tasks and they map directly to the information
    that libpcapng makes available. *)
type frame = {
  ts      : float;   (** timestamp (seconds since the epoch) *)
  caplen  : int;     (** number of bytes present in the capture file *)
  origlen : int;     (** original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data    : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes, length = [caplen] *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Sys_error] if the file cannot be
    opened or the format is not recognised. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a file handle.  The handle is also automatically closed by the OCaml
    garbage collector, but calling [close] explicitly is useful when you want
    to free resources early. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames in the file, applying the supplied function to each
    frame.  The iteration stops as soon as the callback raises an exception,
    which is then propagated to the caller.  The function runs in the same
    thread as the OCaml code, so the callback may freely allocate OCaml values,
    raise exceptions, etc. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Convenience wrapper that opens a file, runs a user function and finally
    closes the file, even if the function raises. *)
val with_file : string -> (t -> 'a) -> 'a
```

